t=Truffaut |editor-first=Fran\u00e7ois |editorlink=Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut |translator1-last=Halsey II |translator1-first=W. W. |translator2-last=Simon |translator2-first=William H. |title=Jean Renoir by Andr\u00e9 Bazin |location=London and New York |publisher=W. H. Allen |pp=294-300 |isbn=0-491-01412-0 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Durgnat |first=Raymond |authorlink=Raymond Durgnat |year=1974 |title=Jean Renoir |location=Berkeley and Los Angeles |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0-520-02283-1 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Faulkner |first=Christopher |year=1979 |title=Jean Renoir, a guide to references and resources |location=Boston |publisher=G. K. Hall |isbn=0-8161-7912-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |last=French |first=Philip |authorlink=Philip French |date=8 July 2007 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2007/jul/08/featuresreview.review6 |title=Other DVDs: Jean Renoir Boxset |work=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Frey |first=Hugo |year=2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6H8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA119 |title=Nationalism and the Cinema in France: Political Mythologies and Film Events, 1945\u20131995 |location=New York and Oxford |publisher=Berghahn Books |isbn=978-1-78238-365-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Hillier |editor-first=Jim |year=1985 |chapter=Appendix 1: ''Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma'' Annual Best Film Listings 1955\u20139 |title=Cahiers du Cinema: The 1950s: Neo-Realism, Hollywood, New Wave |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=0-674-09060-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Hischak |first=Thomas S. |year=2015 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xz99CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA412 |title=The Encyclopedia of Film Composers |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4422-4549-5 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite news |last=Lachize |first=Samuel |date=14 November 1959 |title=''Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe'': fallait-il tenter l'exp\u00e9rience? |trans-title=''Picnic on the Grass'': should the experience be tried? |work=[[L'Humanit\u00e9]] |language=French |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Marie |first=Laurent |year=2013 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxkI2SycFHwC&pg=PA328 |chapter=Renoir and the French Communist Party: The Grand Disillusion |editor1-last=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor2-last=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |editor2-link=Ginette Vincendeau |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=328\u2013346 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=M\u00e9rigeau |first=Pascal |authorlink=Pascal M\u00e9rigeau |year=2017 |orig-year=2012 |title=Jean Renoir: A Biography |translator-last=Benderson |translator-first=Bruce |location=Burbank, California |publisher=Ratpac Press and Running Press |isbn=978-0-7624-5596-6 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Nichols |first=Mary P. |year=2000 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FpEAaYF0jqEC&pg=PA95 |title=Reconstructing Woody: Art, Love, and Life in the Films of Woody Allen |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=0-8476-8989-1 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |last=Oddos |first=Val\u00e9rie |date=6 December 2016 |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/culture/arts-expos/peinture/cagnes-sur-mer-au-milieu-des-oliviers-le-musee-renoir-a-rouvert-ses-portes_3382189.html |title=Cagnes-sur-Mer : au milieu des oliviers, le mus\u00e9e Renoir a rouvert ses portes |trans-title=Cagnes-sur-Mer: in the middle of olive trees, the Renoir museum has reopened its doors |work=[[France Info (TV channel)|France Info]] |language=French |accessdate=20 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last1=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor-last2=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |year=2013 |chapter=Filmography |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=572\u2013584 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1974 |title=My Life and My Films |translator-last=Denny |translator-first=Norman |location=New York |publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=0-306-80457-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1989 |title=Renoir on Renoir: Interviews, Essays, and Remarks |translator-last=Volk |translator-first=Carol |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-38593-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Rohmer |first=\u00c9ric |authorlink=\u00c9ric Rohmer |date=December 1959 |title=Jeunesse de Jean Renoir |trans-title=Jean Renoir's youth |journal=Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma |language=French |issue=102 |pp=1\u20137 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Rivi\u00e8re |editor-first=Marie-Sylvie |year=2018 |chapter-url=https://services.jamesnook.com/services/storage?type=document&id=225222&secret=PDEc67rdlHn3SI3XwAYQIplX2qRvfq61spuq6eE4 |chapter=Go\u00fbter l'Europe |trans-chapter=Taste Europe |title=Quelle Europe voulons-nous ? En suppl\u00e9ment: une s\u00e9lection d'articles et d'entretiens |trans-title=What Europe do we want? Supplement: a selection of articles and interviews |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Semaines sociales de France |pp=45\u201357 |isbn=9782322102792 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Silke |first=James R. |year=2005 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmMH_muqTycC&pg=PA134 |chapter=Jean Renoir on Love, Hollywood, Authors, and Critics |editor-last=Cardullo |editor-first=Bert |title=Jean Renoir: Interviews |location=Jackson, Mississippi |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=1-57806-730-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=''Time Out'' |authorlink=Time Out (magazine) |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-dejeuner-sur-lherbe |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'Herbe |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0052765}}\n* {{Amg movie|38085|Picnic on the Grass}}\n\n{{Jean Renoir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Picnic On The Grass}}\n[[Category:1959 films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean Renoir]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1950s satirical films]]\n[[Category:Artificial insemination]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French satirical films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Greco-Roman mythology]]\n[[Category:Eugenics in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1959 film by Jean Renoir}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Picnic on the Grass\n| image          = Picnic on the Grass poster.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| alt            = The film poster features a painting of the upper body of a nude, dark haired woman. She looks down, is turned away and covers the front of her body with a piece of cloth. Below her is a yellow stripe with the film's French title written in lower case.\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Jean Renoir]]\n| producer       = Ginette Doynel\n| writer         = Jean Renoir\n| starring       = [[Paul Meurisse]]<br />[[Fernand Sardou]]<br />[[Catherine Rouvel]]\n| music          = [[Joseph Kosma]]\n| cinematography = Georges Leclerc\n| editing        = Ren\u00e9e Lichtig\n| studio         = Compagnie Jean Renoir\n| distributor    = [[Path\u00e9]]\n| released       = 11 November 1959\n| runtime        = 92 minutes\n| country        = France\n| language       = French\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n\n'''''Picnic on the Grass''''' ({{lang-fr|Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe}}) is a 1959 French comedy film written and directed by [[Jean Renoir]], starring [[Paul Meurisse]], [[Fernand Sardou]] and [[Catherine Rouvel]]. It is known in the United Kingdom by its original title or in translation as '''''Lunch on the Grass'''''. A satire on contemporary science and politics, it revolves a prominent biologist and politician who wants to replace sex with [[artificial insemination]], but begins to reconsider when a picnic he organizes is interrupted by the forces of nature. The film brings up issues of [[modernity]], [[human reproduction]], youth and [[European integration]]. It ridicules [[Rationalism|rationalist]] [[idealism]] and celebrates a type of [[materialism]] it associates with [[classical mythology]] and [[ancient Greek philosophy]].\n\nThe title is taken from the painting ''[[Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe]]'' by [[\u00c9douard Manet]]. The female lead in ''Picnic on the Grass'' was the first major role for Rouvel, who due to an unusual contract would not appear in another film until 1963. Filming took place around Renoir's childhood home in [[Provence]], and inspiration came from the [[Impressionism|impressionist]] paintings of his father, [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir]]. The filming technique was influenced by [[live television]] and involved [[Multiple-camera setup|multiple cameras]] and direct audio recording.\n\nThe press reviews were generally positive and described the film as charming and beautiful. Negative response came from the political left, where critics disapproved of the film's treatment of [[progress]] and depiction of a European [[superstate]]. The subject of European unification was topical and sensitive due to the creation of the [[European Economic Community]] in 1957. The film was a commercial failure and has attracted little attention from general audiences over the years.\n\n==Plot==\nThe famous biologist \u00c9tienne Alexis is the frontrunner in the upcoming election of the first President of [[United States of Europe|Europe]]. He advocates mandatory [[artificial insemination]] in order to [[Eugenics|improve humanity]] and make it worthy of modern science. He is newly engaged to his German cousin Marie-Charlotte and has invited her to a picnic near his mansion in [[Provence]].\n\nN\u00e9nette, a farmer's daughter, is disappointed with men after a failed relationship. She still wants children and applies to be a test subject for \u00c9tienne's insemination project. She ends up hired as his chambermaid and accompanies the picnic with the other servants. Present at the picnic are several cousins from both France and Germany. They are all stiff, rationally minded and profess belief in scientific [[progress]]. They have invited journalists to document the event as a symbol for the new unified Europe. The picnic takes place next to the ruins of a temple of [[Diana (mythology)|Diana]], the goddess who the ancient Romans believed presided over childbirth. Nearby is also a group of young campers. N\u00e9nette is worried when she spots the goatherd Gaspard. She knows that when Gaspard plays his flute, strange things tend to happen. Gaspard plays and suddenly a strong wind blows away the picnic chairs and tables. As everybody takes cover, \u00c9tienne and N\u00e9nette are separated from the rest.\n\nWhen the wind subsides, they are invited to sit down with the campers. \u00c9tienne explains to the youth how he hopes to eliminate passion. Meanwhile, a [[Bacchanalia]] breaks out among the picnic guests not far away. Leaving the campers to look for Marie-Charlotte, \u00c9tienne ends up seeing N\u00e9nette [[Nude swimming|swimming nude]]. Shortly thereafter, Gaspard plays his flute again, and \u00c9tienne and N\u00e9nette run off into the high reeds. After returning, the two see the cousins and servants leaving in cars. They choose to not approach them and instead rejoin the campers, who offer them to stay the night in their camp. The next morning, \u00c9tienne says he wants to escape from the world for a while, so he and N\u00e9nette go to stay at N\u00e9nette's father Nino's house. \u00c9tienne begins to reconsider the relationship between humans and the natural world. The cousins eventually locate him and come to Nino's house. They convince N\u00e9nette to leave. Realizing she is gone, \u00c9tienne becomes agitated and goes to look for her. Gaspard, the goatherd, recommends him to kneel before his goat and ask for help. After doing so, \u00c9tienne turns ecstatic and shouts \"Down with science!\" before his cousins capture him.\n\n\u00c9tienne goes back to his old life, but on the day of his wedding he discovers N\u00e9nette working in a hotel kitchen. She is happily pregnant with his child. He abruptly brings her, not Marie-Charlotte, to the waiting crowd. He will launch his presidential campaign with a speech about science and nature, and he intends to marry N\u00e9nette.\n\n==Cast==\nCast adapted from ''A Companion to Jean Renoir'' and the [[British Film Institute]].{{sfnm|1a1=Phillips|1a2=Vincendeau|1y=2013|1p=583|2a1=British Film Institute}}\n* [[Paul Meurisse]] as Professor \u00c9tienne Alexis\n* [[Catherine Rouvel]] as N\u00e9nette\n* [[Fernand Sardou]] as Nino, N\u00e9nette's father\n* Jacqueline Morane as Titine, N\u00e9nette's elder sister\n* [[Jean-Pierre Granval]] as Ritou, Titine's husband\n* Ingrid Nordine as Marie-Charlotte\n* [[Charles Blavette]] as Gaspard, the old goatherd\n* [[Paulette Dubost]] as Mlle Forestier, the telephonist\n\n==Themes==\n===Modernity and nature===\n[[File:Pierre-Auguste Renoir 020.jpg|thumb|alt=Oil painting of a nude woman who sits on a rock and leans on a bow. At her feet is a dead deer with its neck pierced by an arrow.|''[[Diana (Renoir painting)|Diana]]'' by Pierre-Auguste Renoir, 1867]]\nThe themes of ''Picnic on the Grass'' revolve modern issues such as artificial insemination, the [[pharmaceutical industry]] and the [[mass media]]. [[Jean Renoir]]'s biographer [[Pascal M\u00e9rigeau]] writes that the film \"deals with disturbingly serious subjects using a farcical tone\".{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=700}} The film historian [[Jean Douchet]] writes that the film should be taken seriously, but describes its story as an invitation to not do so.{{sfn|Douchet|1974|p=295}} Renoir satirizes a [[modernity]] he does not think highly of, and uses story and tone to tell the viewer that it is not very important.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|pp=700\u2013701}}\n\nThe central conflict is built on several [[Dichotomy|dichotomies]]: between the [[Apollonian and Dionysian]], the [[Technocracy|technocratic]] [[Northern Europe]] and underdeveloped [[Mediterranean Basin|Mediterranean region]], and the [[Rationalism|rationalist]] [[idealism]] of [[Postchristianity]] and [[Materialism|materialist]] [[Ancient Greek philosophy|philosophy of ancient Greece]].{{sfn|Douchet|1974|pp=298\u2013299}} ''Picnic on the Grass'' ridicules the idealist notion of progress and celebrates the Dionysian world.{{sfn|Douchet|1974|p=299}} The film portrays an empty spirituality produced by a bureaucratic [[utilitarianism]], and thereby seeks to justify the celebration of a material world imbued with spirit.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=349}} When \u00c9tienne converses with a Christian priest, the two are shown to have disagreements, but simultaneously understand each other well. This is because both still belong to the idealist side in the film's conflict.{{sfn|Douchet|1974|p=299}} According to Douchet, the film sets up a scenario where harmonious equilibrium is achieved when science abandons idealism and submits to a materialist view of nature. This happens when \u00c9tienne marries N\u00e9nette who is pregnant with their naturally conceived child.{{sfn|Douchet|1974|pp=299\u2013300}}\n\n\u00c9tienne is an intellectual who lives in a theoretical world. This makes him similar to the main characters in two earlier works by Renoir: the play ''Orvet'' (1955) and the television film ''[[The Doctor's Horrible Experiment]]'' (1959).{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=314}} \u00c9tienne's eugenic ideology combines rationalism and [[moralism]] in a way that gives [[Darwinism]] an active role in concord with [[individualism]]. [[Human reproduction]] and [[Human evolution|evolution]] become tied to \u00c9tienne's own [[Self-sustainability|self-sufficiency]] and to ideas about social responsibility.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|pp=349\u2013350}} N\u00e9nette is comfortable with her human physicality, but is also driven by self-sufficiency in her wish to have her own child through artificial insemination. She is [[Emancipation|emancipated]] and mobile, and it is her actions that twice bring her to \u00c9tienne. Another\u2014militaristic\u2014type of women's emancipation is represented by Marie-Charlotte.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=350}} Allied against Western rationalism are the gods [[Pan (god)|Pan]] and Diana. Pan is evoked through the flute-playing goatherd, and Diana presides over [[chastity]] and childbirth, which in this [[Classical mythology|classical mythological]] context are aspects of female independence.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=350}}\n\n===Youth===\n[[File:Renoir - PORTRAIT DE JEAN RENOIR, 1910.jpg|thumb|alt=Painted bust portrait of Jean Renoir as a young boy|Portrait of Jean Renoir by Pierre-Auguste Renoir, 1910]]\nRenoir had spent years of his childhood and adolescence in the area where ''Picnic on the Grass'' was filmed.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=700}} He had recently begun to write a book about his father, the painter [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir]], which made him reminisce about his early life.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=699}} Accordng to M\u00e9rigeau, the film was a way for Renoir to confront the boy he once was with the troubling questions of the contemporary world. Renoir's reconnection to his young self is paralleled in the mode of storytelling which is reminiscent of [[Silent film|silent cinema]]. Another parallel is with Renoir's film ''[[Partie de campagne]]'', filmed in 1936, and the similarities in its portrayal of eroticism.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=700}} The filmmaker [[Shirley Clarke]] said that ''Picnic on the Grass'' \"could only have been made by someone of 6 or 60\".{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=354}}\n\n===European integration===\nThe historian Hugo Frey groups ''Picnic on the Grass'' with a number of French comedies that deal with a \"modernist invasion\".{{sfn|Frey|2014|p=119}} These include the films of [[Jacques Tati]], ''[[Mr. Freedom]]'' (1968) by [[William Klein (photographer)|William Klein]] and ''[[The Holes]]'' (1974) by [[Pierre Tchernia]]. Renoir's film stands out in the group because it targets the nascent [[European Union]] rather than the United States.{{sfn|Frey|2014|pp=119\u2013120}}\n\nThe vision of a European [[superstate]] was conceived as the logical continuation of the [[European Economic Community]] (EEC), created in 1957 by the [[Treaty of Rome]]. The film's depiction of a French and German elite couple follows a convention where [[European integration]] is understood as something that particularly concerns France and Germany, or France and [[Germanic-speaking Europe]] overall. The way \u00c9tienne speaks to journalists, with technical and obscure terminology, envisions a future political elite as the only people who will comprehend the European project.{{sfn|Rivi\u00e8re|2018|pp=49\u201350}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nAfter working in [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood]] in the 1940s, Renoir had re-established himself in European cinema following the international success of ''[[The River (1951 film)|The River]]'' (1951). During the 1950s, he developed a more detached and depoliticized approach to filmmaking than before. Simultaneously, he became a more prominent celebrity in France due to television appearances and an increased appreciation for his films from the 1930s. His work became more oriented toward personal subjects.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|pp=328\u2013329}}\n\nThe title of ''Picnic on the Grass'' is taken from the painting ''[[Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe]]'' (1863) by [[\u00c9douard Manet]].{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=699}} Renoir wrote seven versions of the screenplay.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=701}} He made the film through his own production company, Compagnie Jean Renoir. It was the last time he did that; annoyances about logistics during the production made him decide to never produce his own films again. In addition to financial backing from [[Path\u00e9]] and the UCIF, Renoir offered 50% of his earnings from ''[[La Grande Illusion]]'' (1937) as a [[reimbursement]] guarantee, to a limit of 10 million [[French franc|francs]].{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=700}}\n\n===Pre-production===\n[[Catherine Rouvel]]\u2014whose real last name was Rouveyre\u2014did her first major role in ''Picnic on the Grass''. Renoir had met her in 1958, shortly after her 19th birthday, during a tribute to [[Robert J. Flaherty]] at the [[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise]]. She accompanied her husband Georges Rouveyre whose friend Claude Beylie, who was a film critic, introduced her to Renoir. She had enrolled at the drama school Centre d'art dramatique de la rue Blanche a few weeks earlier. The same winter, Renoir contacted her for a reading and a screen test.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=697}} Before she won the role of N\u00e9nette, Renoir considered giving it to the dancer [[Ludmilla Tch\u00e9rina]], whom he had directed in a ballet. He also auditioned [[Mich\u00e8le Mercier]] the same day as Rouveyre. Renoir told Rouveyre in April 1959 that the role was hers. Soon thereafter he suggested that she should change her name to Rouvel.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=698}} For the male lead, Renoir first considered [[Pierre Blanchar]], a man in his mid 60s, before he gave the role to the 20 years younger [[Paul Meurisse]]. Renoir had previously worked with Meurisse in a production of ''[[Julius Caesar (play)|Julius Caesar]]'' and the two were good friends.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=698}} In the role of the goatherd Gaspard he cast [[Charles Blavette]], who had played the title role in Renoir's film ''[[Toni (1935 film)|Toni]]'' (1935).{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=353}}\n\nRenoir rehearsed with the actors for a week before adding technicians to the rehearsals. After this, the director, designer, camera operator and assistant scouted the filming locations. The rehearsals then resumed with markers chalked on the floor corresponding to the locations' topography.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=347}} Working with markers was something Renoir abandoned after ''Picnic on the Grass'', because he thought it was better if the actors could discover the surroundings more freely.{{sfn|Renoir|1989|pp=185\u2013186}}\n\n===Filming and post-production===\n[[File:Cagnes-sur-Mer- Mus\u00e9e Renoir - Ferme -1.JPG|alt=Photograph of a stone house with three floors fronted by an old olive tree|thumb|The old farmhouse at Les Collettes was a filming location. The property was acquired by the city of Cagnes-sur-Mer in 1959 and turned into the Mus\u00e9e Renoir.{{sfn|Oddos|2016}}]]\nFilming took place from 6 to 30 July 1959 at Studio Franc\u0153ur in Paris, and in [[Cagnes-sur-Mer]] and [[La Gaude]] in [[Alpes-Maritimes]].{{sfn|Cin\u00e9-Ressources}} ''Picnic on the Grass'' borrows visual traits from French [[Impressionism|impressionist]] painting, and in particular that of Pierre-Auguste Renoir. This is reflected in the choices of filming locations. Jean Renoir called the film \"something of a homage to the olive-trees under which my father worked so much\".{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=353}} A major location was the property Les Collettes in Cagnes-sur-Mer, which Renoir the elder had bought in 1907, and which had been the home of Jean Renoir for a part of his childhood and adolescence.{{sfnm|1a1=Durgnat|1y=1974|1p=347|2a1=M\u00e9rigeau|2y=2017|2p=700}} Renoir the elder had spent significant time in the town La Gaude where a part of the film was shot. Several of his paintings feature the nearby river Le Coup, which also appears in the film.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=353}}\n\nAnother stylistic choice came from the director's desire to follow impulses on location and encourage improvisation. Renoir said he wanted to make a \"sort of filmed poem\" written in one sitting.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=347}} After the rehearsals, he gave very little instruction to the actors.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=347}} He used a rapid working method influenced by [[live television]].{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=700}} Renoir had first used this technique in his recent television film ''The Doctor's Horrible Experiment'', which he called an \"experimental film\".{{sfn|Renoir|1974|p=276}} He took advantage of the cinematographer's experience from making [[newsreel]] footage. [[Multiple-camera setup|Six cameras were placed around the scene]] to cover all useful angles and shots.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=347}} In addition to saving time and money, the ambition was to retain the uninterrupted, intensive acting of a [[long take]] and still be able to make cuts within the scene.{{sfn|Renoir|1974|pp=276\u2013277}} The method made it possible to record most of the dialogue directly, without problems of continuity due to surrounding sounds such as those from airplanes. Up to twelve microphones were present and only around 20 phrases had to be dubbed in post-production.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=347}}\n\nSeveral key crew members were reused from ''The Doctor's Horrible Experiment''. They included the cinematographer Georges Leclerc and the editor Ren\u00e9e Lichtig. Both would work with Renoir again on his next film, ''[[The Elusive Corporal]]'', which became his final feature film.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=700}} The working method was however not used again.{{sfn|Renoir|1974|p=277}} The original music was composed by [[Joseph Kosma]], who first collaborated with Renoir in 1936 and had provided music for several of his best known films.{{sfn|Hischak|2015|p=412}} The score for ''Picnic on the Grass'' includes a melody the goatherd plays in high pitch on his flute during the wind scene, an upbeat piece played on clarinet in jazz style, and a melody played on flute with harp [[glissando]]s during a lyrical passage.{{sfn|Hischak|2015|p=413}}\n\n==Release==\nPath\u00e9 released ''Picnic on the Grass'' theatrically in France on 11 November 1959.{{sfn|Faulkner|1979|p=160}} In the United Kingdom it was released by Mondial Films in April 1960 under the title ''Lunch on the Grass''.{{sfn|British Board of Film Classification}} It was released in the United States as ''Picnic on the Grass'' on 12 October 1960 by [[Kingsley-International Pictures]].{{sfn|Faulkner|1979|p=160}}\n\nFor the French home-media market, it was first released on [[VHS]] in 1990 by Fil \u00e0 film and on [[DVD]] in 2003 by [[StudioCanal|StudioCanal vid\u00e9o]]. The DVD, which was re-released in 2008, includes a 30-minute documentary directed by Pierre-Fran\u00e7ois Glaymann.{{sfn|BnF Catalogue g\u00e9n\u00e9ral}} The film was released on DVD in the United Kingdom in 2007 by [[StudioCanal UK|Optimum Releasing]], as part of a box set with other Renoir films. The DVD uses the original French title, ''Le D\u00e9jeuner Sur L'Herbe''.{{sfn|French|2007}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Contemporary critical response===\nFrench film critics generally gave ''Picnic on the Grass'' a positive reception, characterized by respect for Renoir. They highlighted the film's connection to impressionism and described it as charming.{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=356}} Rouvel's face was on the cover of the December 1959 issue of ''[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]]'', and the magazine called the film \"the most beautiful of a month rich in masterpieces\".{{sfn|Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, December 1959|loc=inside of the front cover}}{{efn|{{lang|fr|Pour l'\u00e9quipe des \u00ab Cahiers \u00bb et le Conseil des Dix, le film de Jean Renoir est le plus beau d'un mois riche en chefs-d'\u0153uvre.}}}} The review by [[\u00c9ric Rohmer]] stressed the technical novelty of the film, released in \"the year of the '[[French New Wave|New Wave]]'\", which Renoir had influenced profoundly.{{sfn|Rohmer|1959|p=2}}{{efn|{{lang|fr|... l'ann\u00e9e de la \u00ab nouvelle vague \u00bb ...}}}} With its detached and intentionally naive style, Rohmer described it as \"avant-garde popular theater\" in the vein of ''[[Mr Puntila and his Man Matti]]''.{{sfn|Rohmer|1959|p=4}}{{efn|{{lang|fr|... th\u00e9\u00e2tre populaire d'avant-garde ...}}}} For Rohmer, the satire against science should be understood through Renoir's role as an artist, not philosopher or moralist, and not as a rejection of practical science.{{sfn|Rohmer|1959|p=6}} As for politics, he defended the artist's right to look at the problems of the world without being politically engaged.{{sfn|Rohmer|1959|p=7}} ''Picnic on the Grass'' made 13th place on ''Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma'''s composite list of the best films of 1959.{{sfn|Hillier|1985|p=287}} [[Pierre Braunberger]], [[Jean-Luc Godard]], [[Jacques Rivette]], Rohmer and [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]] were among the ''Cahiers'' critics who named it to year-end top ten lists.{{sfn|Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma, February 1960|pp=1\u20132}}\n\n[[File:Jean Renoir (1959).tif|thumb|left|alt=Black and white photograph of Jean Renoir in his mid 60s|Jean Renoir in 1959]]\nRenoir had supported the [[French Communist Party]] (PCF) in the 1930s, but ''Picnic on the Grass'' received negative reviews from critics with [[Communism|communist]] sympathies. It was released at a time when the PCF idealized progress and its members were enthusiastic about the [[Soviet space program]].{{sfn|Marie|2013|pp=328 and 340}} Samuel Lachize of ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'' considered the film flawed on a technical level, and criticized its lack of a clear choice between scientific progress and the rejection of it. He dismissed the philosophical content, which he took as a pseudo-[[Jean-Jacques Rousseau|Rousseauesque]] message about going [[back to nature]].{{sfn|Lachize|1959|p=2|ps=, quoted in {{harvtxt|Marie|2013|pp=338\u2013339}}}} ''The Doctor's Horrible Experiment'' received a similar treatment from communist critics.{{sfn|Marie|2013|pp=339\u2013340}} Left-wing critics also criticized ''Picnic on the Grass'' for its eventual acceptance of a European superstate, which was taken as an approval of the EEC, opposed by the left at the time. Furthermore upsetting for the left, the reservations \u00c9tienne develops were interpreted as support for [[Charles de Gaulle]]'s {{lang|fr|Europe des patries}} (\"Europe of fatherlands\").{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|pp=350\u2013352}} In the 1970s, the film critic [[Raymond Durgnat]] related the response to the left's own struggle to oppose the EEC without turning to patriotism. Durgnat wrote that it was \"perhaps not too unkind to suggest that my left-wing colleagues were making their 'lost leader' a scapegoat for the very real difficulties of the left itself\u2014or should one say the lefts themselves?\"{{sfn|Durgnat|1974|p=352}}\n\nGideon Bachmann wrote in ''[[Film Quarterly]]'' that many American critics gave ''Picnic on the Grass'' a \"silly treatment\", because they did not understand it through its director as a person. He used [[Hollis Alpert]] of the ''[[Saturday Review (U.S. magazine)|Saturday Review]]'' as a positive counterexample.{{sfn|Bachmann|1960|p=40}} Alpert called it \"a nonsensically unconventional movie\" where viewers \"would be better off not trying to make sense or logic out of it, but simply allowing M. Renoir to have his day in the fields\".{{sfn|Alpert|1960|p=34}} Bachmann wrote that the film is reminiscent of Tati's films, both in message and how the message is conveyed through colors.{{sfn|Bachmann|1960|p=40}} He contrasted the seeming simplicity with the serious content, and the impressionism with the surreal elements. He called it \"almost facile in impact but lasting in the perturbations it causes\".{{sfn|Bachmann|1960|p=41}}\n\n===Retrospective critical response===\n''Picnic on the Grass'' has received little attention from general audiences over time, but it has been embraced by individual critics.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=701}} In 2006, Luc Arbona of ''[[Les Inrockuptibles]]'' called it an \"extraordinary pamphlet\" portraying \"the peddlers of progress\" who \"only care about security, asepticity and uniformity\".{{sfn|Arbona|2006}}{{efn|{{lang|fr|Renoir r\u00e9alise ici un extraordinaire pamphlet o\u00f9 il met en sc\u00e8ne les camelots du progr\u00e8s qui se contrefoutent du monde, de la nature et ne se soucient que de s\u00e9curisation, d'aseptisation et d'uniformisation.}}}} Arbona called the satire \"abuntant and exhilirating\" and the film \"brilliantly prophetic\", because by the time of his writing, Arbona wrote, \"these progress-obsessed, these ad-agency apostles who have nothing but the politically correct to say, have seized power and are leading the dance.\"{{sfn|Arbona|2006}}{{efn|{{lang|fr|Satire foisonnante et jubilatoire, Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe est g\u00e9nialement proph\u00e9tique. Quarante-cinq ans apr\u00e8s, ces enrag\u00e9s du progr\u00e8s, ces ap\u00f4tres d'une soci\u00e9t\u00e9 publicitaire qui n'ont que le politiquement correct \u00e0 la bouche, ont pris le pouvoir et m\u00e8nent la danse.}}}} ''[[The New Yorker]]'''s [[Richard Brody]] wrote about the film in conjunction with [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012. Taking its message as a rejection of modern technology, he still compared it favorably to [[Steven Soderbergh]]'s ''[[Contagion (2011 film)|Contagion]]'', which shows science and the government triumphant in a crisis of natural origin. Brody made a point of separating art and politics: \"Looking to filmmakers for practical advice in the teeth of trouble is usually as pointless as turning to politicians for visions of beauty.\"{{sfn|Brody|2012}} ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' called it \"one of Renoir's most ravishing, and simultaneously most irritating films\", because the \"sumptuous photography\" repeatedly \"collapses into cold argument\".{{sfn|Time Out}}\n\n===Box office===\n''Picnic on the Grass'' had 757,024 admissions in France.{{sfn|AlloCin\u00e9}} It was a commercial failure. Renoir addressed this in a letter to the producer Ginette Doynel a few weeks after the Paris premiere. He wrote that the failure had given him a distaste for film and television work in general. He would instead focus on his teaching position at the [[University of California, Berkeley]], his plays, and his book about his father.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=701}} ''Picnic on the Grass'' later had a significant theatrical run in the United States, which delighted Renoir.{{sfn|Silke|2005|p=134}}\n\n==Legacy==\nRouvel signed an unusual contract which had the practical effect that Renoir had to approve all her engagements for the next three years. Renoir decided to keep her away from the film industry and only accepted offers of theater roles. He rejected roles in ''[[The Green Mare (film)|The Green Mare]]'' and a film by [[G\u00e9rard Oury]]. Rouvel returned to film acting in [[Claude Chabrol]]'s ''[[Landru (film)|Bluebeard]]'', released in January 1963.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|pp=699\u2013700}}\n\nThe film ''[[Le Bonheur (1965 film)|Le Bonheur]]'' (1965) directed by [[Agn\u00e8s Varda]] pays tribute to ''Picnic on the Grass'' by including a passage which plays on a television screen.{{sfn|M\u00e9rigeau|2017|p=734}} The film scholar Nancy Pogel argues in her book on [[Woody Allen]] that Allen's ''[[A Midsummer Night's Sex Comedy]]'' (1982) is indebted to ''Picnic on the Grass''.{{sfn|Nichols|2000|p=95}}\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[The Farm at Les Collettes, Cagnes]]''\n* [[France\u2013Germany relations]]\n* [[Pan in popular culture]]\n* [[Physis]] and [[techne]]\n* [[Reproduction and pregnancy in speculative fiction]]\n\n==References==\n===Original quotations===\n{{notelist}}\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n: {{cite web |author=[[AlloCin\u00e9]] |url=http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=72342.html |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe |language=French |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208035056/http://www.allocine.fr/film/fichefilm_gen_cfilm=72342.html |publisher=Tiger Global |archive-date=8 December 2015 |accessdate=17 March 2020 |ref=CITEREFAlloCin\u00e9 }}\n\n: {{cite news |last=Alpert |first=Hollis |authorlink=Hollis Alpert |date=15 October 1960 |url=https://www.unz.com/print/SaturdayRev-1960oct15-00034/ |title=Panic on the Grass |work=[[Saturday Review (U.S. magazine)|Saturday Review]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite news |last=Arbona |first=Luc |date=17 August 2006 |url=https://www.lesinrocks.com/cinema/films-a-l-affiche/le-dejeuner-sur-lherbe/ |title=le d\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe |work=[[Les Inrockuptibles]] |language=French |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Bachmann |first=Gideon |year=1960 |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'Herbe |journal=[[Film Quarterly]] |volume=14 |issue=2 |pp=40\u201341 |doi=10.2307/1210350 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=BnF Catalogue g\u00e9n\u00e9ral |url=https://data.bnf.fr/en/16179534/le_dejeuner_sur_l_herbe___film/ |title=Le d\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe : film |publisher=[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/lunch-grass-1959 |title=Lunch on the Grass |accessdate=17 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=[[British Film Institute]] |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b6a8a022a |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe |accessdate=18 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite news |last=Brody |first=Richard |authorlink=Richard Brody |date=29 October 2012 |url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/watching-sandy-with-jean-renoir |title=Watching Sandy with Jean Renoir |work=[[The New Yorker]] |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |year=1959 |title=Notre couverture |trans-title=Our cover |journal=[[Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma]] |language=French |volume=17 |issue=12 |ref=CITEREFCahiers du cin\u00e9ma, December 1959 }}\n\n: {{cite journal |year=1960 |title=Les dix meilleurs films de l'ann\u00e9e |trans-title=The ten best films of the year |journal=Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma |language=French |volume=18 |issue=2 |ref=CITEREFCahiers du cin\u00e9ma, February 1960 }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=[[Cin\u00e9-Ressources]] |url=http://cinema.encyclopedie.films.bifi.fr/index.php?pk=50831 |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe |language=French |publisher=[[Cin\u00e9math\u00e8que Fran\u00e7aise]] |accessdate=26 February 2020 |ref=CITEREFCin\u00e9-Ressources }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Douchet |first=Jean |authorlink=Jean Douchet |year=1974 |chapter=Le Dejeuner sur l'Herbe (1959) (Picnic on the Grass, 1960) |editor-last=Truffaut |editor-first=Fran\u00e7ois |editorlink=Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut |translator1-last=Halsey II |translator1-first=W. W. |translator2-last=Simon |translator2-first=William H. |title=Jean Renoir by Andr\u00e9 Bazin |location=London and New York |publisher=W. H. Allen |pp=294-300 |isbn=0-491-01412-0 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Durgnat |first=Raymond |authorlink=Raymond Durgnat |year=1974 |title=Jean Renoir |location=Berkeley and Los Angeles |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0-520-02283-1 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Faulkner |first=Christopher |year=1979 |title=Jean Renoir, a guide to references and resources |location=Boston |publisher=G. K. Hall |isbn=0-8161-7912-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |last=French |first=Philip |authorlink=Philip French |date=8 July 2007 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2007/jul/08/featuresreview.review6 |title=Other DVDs: Jean Renoir Boxset |work=[[The Observer]] |accessdate=29 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Frey |first=Hugo |year=2014 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U6H8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA119 |title=Nationalism and the Cinema in France: Political Mythologies and Film Events, 1945\u20131995 |location=New York and Oxford |publisher=Berghahn Books |isbn=978-1-78238-365-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Hillier |editor-first=Jim |year=1985 |chapter=Appendix 1: ''Cahiers du Cin\u00e9ma'' Annual Best Film Listings 1955\u20139 |title=Cahiers du Cinema: The 1950s: Neo-Realism, Hollywood, New Wave |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |publisher=Harvard University Press |isbn=0-674-09060-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Hischak |first=Thomas S. |year=2015 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Xz99CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA412 |title=The Encyclopedia of Film Composers |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1-4422-4549-5 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite news |last=Lachize |first=Samuel |date=14 November 1959 |title=''Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'herbe'': fallait-il tenter l'exp\u00e9rience? |trans-title=''Picnic on the Grass'': should the experience be tried? |work=[[L'Humanit\u00e9]] |language=French |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Marie |first=Laurent |year=2013 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FxkI2SycFHwC&pg=PA328 |chapter=Renoir and the French Communist Party: The Grand Disillusion |editor1-last=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor2-last=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |editor2-link=Ginette Vincendeau |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=328\u2013346 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=M\u00e9rigeau |first=Pascal |authorlink=Pascal M\u00e9rigeau |year=2017 |orig-year=2012 |title=Jean Renoir: A Biography |translator-last=Benderson |translator-first=Bruce |location=Burbank, California |publisher=Ratpac Press and Running Press |isbn=978-0-7624-5596-6 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Nichols |first=Mary P. |year=2000 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FpEAaYF0jqEC&pg=PA95 |title=Reconstructing Woody: Art, Love, and Life in the Films of Woody Allen |location=Lanham, Maryland |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=0-8476-8989-1 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |last=Oddos |first=Val\u00e9rie |date=6 December 2016 |url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/culture/arts-expos/peinture/cagnes-sur-mer-au-milieu-des-oliviers-le-musee-renoir-a-rouvert-ses-portes_3382189.html |title=Cagnes-sur-Mer : au milieu des oliviers, le mus\u00e9e Renoir a rouvert ses portes |trans-title=Cagnes-sur-Mer: in the middle of olive trees, the Renoir museum has reopened its doors |work=[[France Info (TV channel)|France Info]] |language=French |accessdate=20 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last1=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor-last2=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |year=2013 |chapter=Filmography |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=572\u2013584 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1974 |title=My Life and My Films |translator-last=Denny |translator-first=Norman |location=New York |publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=0-306-80457-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1989 |title=Renoir on Renoir: Interviews, Essays, and Remarks |translator-last=Volk |translator-first=Carol |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-38593-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Rohmer |first=\u00c9ric |authorlink=\u00c9ric Rohmer |year=1959 |title=Jeunesse de Jean Renoir |trans-title=Jean Renoir's youth |journal=Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma |language=French |volume=17 |issue=12 |pp=1\u20137 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Rivi\u00e8re |editor-first=Marie-Sylvie |year=2018 |chapter-url=https://services.jamesnook.com/services/storage?type=document&id=225222&secret=PDEc67rdlHn3SI3XwAYQIplX2qRvfq61spuq6eE4 |chapter=Go\u00fbter l'Europe |trans-chapter=Taste Europe |title=Quelle Europe voulons-nous ? En suppl\u00e9ment: une s\u00e9lection d'articles et d'entretiens |trans-title=What Europe do we want? Supplement: a selection of articles and interviews |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Semaines sociales de France |pp=45\u201357 |isbn=9782322102792 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Silke |first=James R. |year=2005 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmMH_muqTycC&pg=PA134 |chapter=Jean Renoir on Love, Hollywood, Authors, and Critics |editor-last=Cardullo |editor-first=Bert |title=Jean Renoir: Interviews |location=Jackson, Mississippi |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=1-57806-730-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=''Time Out'' |authorlink=Time Out (magazine) |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-dejeuner-sur-lherbe |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'Herbe |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0052765}}\n* {{Amg movie|38085|Picnic on the Grass}}\n\n{{Jean Renoir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Picnic On The Grass}}\n[[Category:1959 films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean Renoir]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1950s satirical films]]\n[[Category:Artificial insemination]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French satirical films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Greco-Roman mythology]]\n[[Category:Eugenics in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Ffranc", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reference format", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picnic_on_the_Grass"}
{"title_page": "George Reeves", "text_new": "{{for|the Texas politician|George R. Reeves}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}<!--[[WP:STRONGNAT]]-->\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = George Reeves\n| image                     = George Reeves - 1948.jpg\n| image_size                =\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   = Reeves in ''[[The Sainted Sisters]]'' (1948)\n| birth_name                = George Keefer Brewer\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date|1914|1|5|mf=y}}\n| birth_place               = [[Woolstock, Iowa]], U.S.\n| death_date                = {{Death date and age|1959|6|16|1914|1|5|mf=y}}\n| death_place               = [[Benedict Canyon, Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause               = Gunshot\n| resting_place             = Mountain View Cemetery<br />Pasadena Mausoleum, Sunrise Corridor<br />[[Altadena, California]], U.S.\n| resting_place_coordinates = {{Coord |34.1840 |-118.1497 |region:US-CA_type:landmark |display=inline}}\n| nationality               = American\n| other_names               = George Bessolo\n| education                 = [[Polytechnic School]] (1929), Pasadena, California    \n| alma_mater                = [[Pasadena Junior College]]\n| occupation                = Actor\n| years_active              = 1933\u20131959\n| height                    = 6 ft 2 in\n| known_for                 = Portraying [[Superman]] in ''[[Adventures of Superman (TV series)|Adventures of Superman]]''\n| spouse                    = {{Marriage|Ellanora Needles|1940|1950|reason=div}}\n}}\n\n'''George Reeves''' (born '''George Keefer Brewer'''; January 5, 1914&nbsp;\u2013 June 16, 1959) was an American [[actor]]. He is best known for his role as [[Superman]] in the 1952-1958 television program ''[[Adventures of Superman (TV series)|Adventures of Superman]]''.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=George Reeves|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/107820/George-Reeves}}</ref><ref name=NYT2>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Luc Moullet and George Reeves|first=Dave|last=Kehr|date=January 2, 2007|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/02/movies/homevideo/02dvd.html?fta=y&_r=0}}</ref>\n\nHis death at age 45 from a gunshot remains a controversial subject; the official finding was suicide, but some believe that he was murdered or the victim of an accidental shooting.<ref name=NYT/><ref name=NYT2/><ref>{{cite web|work=[[The Guardian]]|title=Who killed Superman?|date=17 November 2006|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2006/nov/18/features.weekend1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=August 20, 2006|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=The (Tinsel) Town That Ate Superman|first=Kristopher|last=Tapley|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/20/movies/20tapl.html?pagewanted=print}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.franksreelreviews.com/shorttakes/supermanreeves.htm|title=The Death of George Reeves \u2013 The Original Superman|publisher=Franksreelreviews.com|date=2010-04-16|accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref><ref>Henderson, Jan Alan, Speeding Bullet, M. Bifulco, 1999; {{ISBN|0-9619596-4-9}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nReeves was born January 5, 1914<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/05/UPI-Almanac-for-Saturday-Jan-5-2019/9081546481545/ |title= UPI Almanac for Saturday, Jan. 5, 2019 |agency=[[United Press International]]|date=January 5, 2019|accessdate=September 6, 2019|archivedate=January 5, 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190105134420/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/05/UPI-Almanac-for-Saturday-Jan-5-2019/9081546481545/|url-status=live|quote= actor George Reeves (TV's Superman) in 1914}}</ref><ref>Reeves' [[gravestone|mausoleum plaque]] erroneously lists his birth date as \"1/6/1914,\" or January 6, 1914.</ref> as George Keefer Brewer in [[Woolstock, Iowa]], the son of Donald Carl Brewer and Helen Lescher. Reeves was born five months into their marriage<ref>Fox, Alma Archer. \"My Cousin Superman\", ''Galesburg Register-Mail'', June 15, 1979.</ref> and the couple separated soon after Reeves's birth. At this time, Reeves and his mother moved from Iowa to her home of [[Galesburg, Illinois]].<ref name=\"Galesburg RegMail article\">{{cite web|url=http://www.galesburg.com/article/20140920/ENTERTAINMENTLIFE/140929987|title='Superman' absent in Mom's time of need|publisher=Galesburg Register Mail|date=September 20, 2014|accessdate=March 12, 2015|author=Tom Wilson}}</ref>\n\nLater, Reeves's mother,<ref>Helen Roberta Lescher Brewer Bessolo (1894\u20131964) was the daughter of George Christian Lescher and Eliza Jane McKenzie, she died in a Pasadena hospital on June 18, 1964.</ref> who was of [[German descent]], moved to California to stay with her sister. There she met and married Frank Joseph Bessolo while Reeves's father married Helen Schultz in 1925. Reeves reportedly never saw his father again. In 1927, Frank Bessolo adopted George as his own son, and the boy took on his stepfather's last name, becoming '''George Bessolo'''.<ref name=\"Superman Homepage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.supermanhomepage.com/tv/tv.php?topic=cast-crew/george-reeves|title=Superman Homepage|accessdate=June 16, 2007}}</ref> The Bessolo marriage lasted 15 years, ending in divorce, with the couple separating while Reeves was away visiting relatives. When he returned, his mother told him his stepfather had committed suicide.\n\nAccording to biographer [[Jim Beaver]], Reeves did not know for several years that Bessolo was still alive. Reeves began acting and singing in high school and continued performing on stage as a student at [[Pasadena Junior College]].<ref>''Pasadena Junior College Courier'', 1934</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\nWhile studying acting at the [[Pasadena Playhouse]], Reeves met his future wife, Ellanora Needles. They married on September 22, 1940, in [[San Gabriel, California]], at the Church of Our Savior. They had no children and divorced 10 years later.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nReeves's film career began in 1939 when he was cast as Stuart Tarleton (incorrectly listed in the film's credits as Brent Tarleton), one of [[Scarlett O'Hara]]'s suitors in ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]''. It was a minor role, but he and [[Fred Crane (actor)|Fred Crane]] were in the film's opening scene. (Reeves and Crane both dyed their hair red to portray the Tarleton twins.) After ''Gone with the Wind'' was filmed, Reeves returned to the Pasadena Playhouse and was given the lead role in the play ''Poncho''. This part directly led to him being contracted to [[Warner Brothers]].<ref name=CloserOwn>{{cite web |last=Gross |first=Ed |title=The Life and Tragic Death of \u2018Superman\u2019 Star George Reeves \u2014 Plus the Actor in his Own Words |url=https://www.supermanhomepage.com/tv/tv.php?topic=cast-crew/george-reeves |website=[[Closer (magazine)|Closer]] |accessdate=26 December 2019 |date=October 28, 2019}}</ref> Warner changed his professional name to George Reeves.<ref name=\"Superman Homepage\"/> His ''Gone with the Wind'' screen credit reflects the change. Between the start of ''Gone With the Wind'' production and its release 12 months later, several films on his Warner contract were made and released, making ''Gone With the Wind'' his first film role, but his fifth film release.\n\nHe starred in a number of two-reel short subjects and appeared in several B-pictures, including two with [[Ronald Reagan]] and three with [[James Cagney]] (''[[Torrid Zone]]'', ''[[The Fighting 69th]]'', and ''[[The Strawberry Blonde]]''). These roles did little to advance Reeves' career, and his contract with Warners was dissolved by mutual consent.<ref name=CloserOwn/>\n\nReleased from his Warner contract, he signed a contract at [[Twentieth Century-Fox]], but was released after only a handful of films, one of which was the [[Charlie Chan]] movie ''[[Dead Men Tell]]''. Twentieth Century-Fox loaned him to producer [[Alexander Korda]] to co-star with [[Merle Oberon]] in ''[[Lydia (film)|Lydia]]'',<ref name=CloserOwn/> a box-office failure. He freelanced, looking to find work in westerns.<ref name=CloserOwn/> His friend [[Teddi Sherman]] introduced him to her producer father [[Harry Sherman]], who asked Reeves to do a [[screen test]] with Teddi for the [[Hopalong Cassidy]] films. Reeves and Sherman impressed the casting director by performing seven pages of script without pause in a single take.<ref name=CloserOwn/> Reeves appeared in five Hopalong Cassidy westerns before being cast as Lieutenant John Summers opposite [[Claudette Colbert]] in ''[[So Proudly We Hail!]]'' (1942), a war drama for [[Paramount Pictures]], who signed Reeves up for two films a year.<ref name=CloserOwn/>\n\nHowever, Reeves was inspired by ''So Proudly We Hail!'' to put his budding acting career on hold and enlist in the [[U.S. Army]].<ref name=CloserOwn/> He was drafted in early 1943.<ref>U.S. World War II Army Enlistment Records 1938\u20131946, dated 24 March 1943</ref> He was assigned to the [[U.S. Army Air Forces]] and performed in the USAAF's [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] show ''[[Winged Victory (play)|Winged Victory]]''. The long Broadway run was followed by a national tour and a [[Winged Victory (film)|movie]] version. Reeves was then transferred to the Army Air Forces' [[First Motion Picture Unit]], where he made training films.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\nDischarged at the war's end, Reeves returned to Hollywood. However, many studios were slowing down their production schedules, and some production units had shut down completely. He appeared in a pair of outdoor thrillers with [[Ralph Byrd]]. As more and more time passed between lower and lower-paying acting jobs, Reeves was reduced to appearing in a low-budget serial produced by [[Sam Katzman]], ''[[The Adventures of Sir Galahad]]'', and taking a second job digging [[cesspool]]s.<ref name=CloserOwn/> Reeves fit the rugged requirements of the roles and, with his retentive memory for dialogue, he did well under rushed production conditions. He was able to play against type and starred as a villainous gold hunter in a [[Johnny Weissmuller]] [[Jungle Jim]] film. Separated from his wife (their divorce became final in 1950), Reeves moved to [[New York City]] in 1949. He performed on live television anthology programs, as well as on radio, and then returned to Hollywood in 1951 for a role in a [[Fritz Lang]] film, ''[[Rancho Notorious]]''.<ref>\"George Reeves Returns\", ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', April 11, 1951, p. 6</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Reeves played a minor character, Sergeant Maylon Stark, in ''[[From Here To Eternity]]''. The film won the [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and gave Reeves the distinction of appearing in two \"Best Picture\" films.\n\n===Superman===\n<!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:Superman and the Mole Men video capture.JPG|thumb|200px|Reeves and [[Phyllis Coates]] in ''[[Superman and the Mole Men]]'']] -->\nIn June 1951, Reeves was offered the role of [[Superman]] in a new television series<ref>\"Reeves Now Superman\", ''Hollywood Reporter'', June 25, 1951, p. 7.</ref> titled ''[[Adventures of Superman (TV series)|Adventures of Superman]]''. He was initially reluctant to take the role because, like many actors of his time, he considered television unimportant and believed few would see his work. The half-hour films were shot on tight schedules; at least two shows were made every six days. According to commentaries on the ''Adventures of Superman'' DVD sets, multiple scripts would be filmed simultaneously to take advantage of the standing sets so that, for example, all the \"Perry White's office\" scenes for three or four episodes would be shot the same day and the various \"apartment\" scenes would be done consecutively.\n\nReeves's career as Superman had begun with ''[[Superman and the Mole Men]]'', a film intended both as a B-picture and as the pilot for the TV series. Immediately after completing it, Reeves and the crew began production of the first season's episodes, all shot over 13 weeks in the summer of 1951. The series went on the air the following year, and Reeves was amazed at becoming a national celebrity. In 1952, the struggling [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC Network]] purchased the show for national broadcast, which gave him greater visibility.\n\nThe Superman cast members had restrictive contracts which prevented them from taking other work that might interfere with the series. Except for the second season, the Superman schedule was brief (13 shows shot two per week, a total of seven weeks out of a year), but all had a \"30-day clause\", which meant that the producers could demand their exclusive services for a new season on four weeks' notice. This prevented long-term work on major films with long schedules, stage plays which might lead to a lengthy run, or any other series work.<ref name=\"Grossman, page 121\">Grossman, p. 121.</ref>\n\nReeves, however, earned additional income from personal appearances. He had affection for his young fans, and took his role model status seriously.<ref name=CloserOwn/> He avoided cigarettes where children could see him and eventually quit smoking. He kept his private life discreet. Nevertheless, he had a romantic relationship with a married ex-showgirl eight years his senior, [[Toni Mannix]], wife of [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] general manager [[Eddie Mannix]].\n\nIn the documentary ''[[Look, Up in the Sky: The Amazing Story of Superman]]'', [[Jack Larson]] described how when he first met Reeves he told him that he enjoyed his performance in ''So Proudly We Hail!'' According to Larson, Reeves said that if Mark Sandrich had not died, he would not be there in \"this monkey suit\".{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} According to Larson, Reeves also said he would feel better about the role if he knew he had any adult fans, and never learned that ''Adventures of Superman'' had adult fans even during its original broadcast run.<ref name=CloserOwn/>\n\nBetween the first and second seasons of ''Superman'', Reeves got sporadic acting assignments in one-shot TV anthology programs and in two feature films, ''[[Forever Female]]'' (1953) and [[Fritz Lang]]'s ''[[The Blue Gardenia]]'' (1953), but by the time the series was airing nationwide, Reeves found himself so [[Typecasting (acting)|associated]] with Superman and Clark Kent that it was difficult for him to find other roles.\n\nReeves worked tirelessly with Toni Mannix to raise money to fight [[myasthenia gravis]]. He served as national chairman for the Myasthenia Gravis Foundation in 1955. During the second season, Reeves appeared in a short film for the Treasury Department entitled ''[[Stamp Day for Superman]]'', in which he caught the villains and told children why they should invest in government [[savings stamp]]s.\n[[File:Stamp Day for Superman.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Screen capture of Reeves as Superman in the U.S. government film ''[[Stamp Day for Superman]]'']]\n\nAfter two seasons, Reeves was dissatisfied with his salary and the show's one-dimensional role. He was 40 years old and wished to quit and move on with his career. The producers looked elsewhere for a new star.<ref>''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', September 27, 1954.</ref>\n\nReeves established his own production company and conceived a TV adventure series called ''Port of Entry'' which would be shot on location in Hawaii and Mexico, writing the pilot script himself. However, ''Superman'' producers offered him a salary increase and he returned to the series.<ref>''Variety'', October 27, 1954.</ref> He was reportedly making $5,000 (about $50,000 in 2018 dollars) per week, but only while the show was in production (about eight weeks each year).<ref name=\"Grossman, page 121\"/> As for ''Port of Entry'', Reeves was never able to gain financing for the project, and the show was never made.\n\nIn 1957, the producers considered a theatrical film ''Superman and the Secret Planet''. A script was commissioned from David Chantler, who had written many of the TV scripts. In 1959, however, negotiations began for a renewal of the series, with 26&nbsp;episodes scheduled to go into production. By mid 1959, contracts were signed, costumes refitted, and new teleplay writers assigned. [[Noel Neill]] was quoted as saying that the cast of ''Superman'' was ready to do a new series of the still-popular show.<ref>''DC Comics: Sixty Years of the World's Favorite Comic Book Heroes,'' no page cited.</ref>\n\nAttempting to showcase his versatility, Reeves sang on the [[Tony Bennett]] show in August 1956.<ref>Grossman, p. 45.</ref> He appeared as Superman on ''[[I Love Lucy]]'' (Episode #165, \"[[Lucy and Superman]]\") in 1957. Character actor [[Ben Welden]] had acted with Reeves in the Warner Bros. days and frequently guest-starred on ''Superman''. He said, \"After the ''I Love Lucy'' show, Superman was no longer a challenge to him.... I know he enjoyed the role, but he used to say, 'Here I am, wasting my life.'\"<ref>Grossman, p. 151.</ref> His good friend [[Bill Walsh (producer)|Bill Walsh]], a producer at [[Disney]] Studios, gave Reeves a prominent role in ''[[Westward Ho the Wagons!]]'' (1956), in which Reeves wore a beard and mustache. It was to be his final feature film appearance.\n\nReeves, Noel Neill, [[Natividad Vac\u00edo]], [[Gene LeBell]], and a trio of musicians toured with a public appearance show from 1957 onward. The first half of the show was a ''Superman'' sketch in which Reeves and Neill performed with LeBell as a villain called \"Mr. [[Kryptonite]]\" who captured Lois Lane. Kent then rushed offstage to return as Superman, who came to the rescue and fought with the bad guy. The second half of the show was Reeves out of costume and as himself, singing and accompanying himself on the guitar. Vacio and Neill accompanied him in duets.<ref>Grossman, p. 54.</ref>\n\nReeves and Toni Mannix split in 1958, and Reeves announced his engagement to society playgirl Leonore Lemmon. Reeves was apparently scheduled to marry Lemmon on June 19 and then spend their honeymoon in Tijuana. He complained to friends, columnists, and his mother of his financial problems. The planned revival of ''Superman'' was apparently a small lifeline. Reeves had also hoped to direct a low-budget science-fiction film written by a friend from his Pasadena Playhouse days, and he had discussed the project with his first Lois Lane, [[Phyllis Coates]], the previous year.<ref>Grossman, p. 58.</ref> However, Reeves and his partner failed to find financing, and the film was never made. Another Superman stage show was scheduled for July<ref>New York Post, June 17, 1959.</ref> with a planned stage tour of [[Australia]]. Reeves had options for making a living, but those options apparently all involved playing Superman again\u2014a role that he was not eager to reprise at age 45.\n\nJack Larson and Noel Neill both remembered Reeves as a noble Southern gentleman (even though he was from Iowa) with a sign on his dressing room door that said \"Honest George, the people's friend\".<ref>''[[Look, Up in the Sky: The Amazing Story of Superman]]''.</ref> Reeves had been made a \"[[Kentucky Colonel]]\" during a publicity trip in the South, and the sign on his dressing room door was replaced with a new one that read \"Honest George, also known as Col. Reeves\", created by the show's prop department. A photo of a smiling Reeves and the sign appears in Gary Grossman's book about the show.\n\n==Death==\n{{more citations needed section|date=May 2010}}\nReeves died of a gunshot wound to the head in the upstairs bedroom of his home in [[Benedict Canyon, Los Angeles, California|Benedict Canyon]] between 1:30 and 2:00&nbsp;a.m. on June 16, 1959, according to the Los Angeles Police Department report. The police arrived within the hour. Present in the house at the time of the incident were Leonore Lemmon (Reeves' fianc\u00e9e), William Bliss, writer Robert Condon, and Carol Van Ronkel, who lived a few blocks away with her husband, screenwriter Rip Van Ronkel.\n\nAccording to these witnesses, Lemmon and Reeves had been dining and drinking earlier in the evening in the company of writer Condon, who was [[Ghostwriter|ghostwriting]] an autobiography of prizefighter [[Archie Moore]]. Reeves and Lemmon had an argument at the restaurant in front of Condon, and the three of them returned home. However, Lemmon stated in interviews with Reeves' biographer Jim Beaver that she and Reeves had not accompanied friends to the restaurant but rather to wrestling matches. Contemporaneous news items indicate that Reeves' friend [[Gene LeBell]] was wrestling that night\u2014yet LeBell's own recollections are that he did not see Reeves after a workout session earlier in the day.\n\nSometime near midnight, after Reeves had gone to bed, an impromptu party began when Bliss and Carol Van Ronkel arrived at the Reeves home. Reeves angrily came downstairs and complained about the noise. After blowing off steam, he stayed with the guests for a while, had a drink, and then returned upstairs again in a bad mood. The guests later heard a single gunshot from upstairs. Bliss ran upstairs into Reeves' bedroom and found him lying across the bed dead, his naked body facing upward and his feet on the floor. It is believed that this corroborated Reeves' sitting position on the edge of the bed when he allegedly shot himself, after which his body fell back on the bed and the .30 caliber (7.65\u00d721mm) [[Luger P08 pistol|Luger]] pistol fell between his feet.\n\nStatements made by the witnesses to the police and to the press essentially agree. Neither Leonore Lemmon nor other guests who were at the scene made any apology for their delay in calling the police after hearing the fatal gunshot that killed Reeves; the shock of the death, the lateness of the hour, and their state of intoxication were given as reasons for the delay. Police said that all of the witnesses present were extremely inebriated and that coherent stories were very difficult to obtain from them.\n\nIn contemporary news articles, Lemmon attributed Reeves' alleged suicide to depression caused by his \"failed career\" and inability to find more work. The report made by the Los Angeles Police states, \"[Reeves was]... depressed because he couldn't get the sort of parts he wanted.\" Newspapers and wire-service reports quoted LAPD Sergeant V.A. Peterson as saying: \"Miss Lemmon blurted, 'He's probably going to go shoot himself.' A noise was heard upstairs. She continued, 'He's opening a drawer to get the gun.' A shot was heard. 'See there\u2014I told you so!'\"'<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=EQMdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7ooEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7331,1693817&dq=george+reeves+lenore+lemmon+i+told+you+so&hl=en|title=Actor Commits Suicide|date=June 17, 1959|work=Sarasota Journal|page=14|accessdate=January 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe official story given by Lemmon to the police placed her in the living room with party guests at the time of the shooting, but hearsay statements from Fred Crane, Reeves' friend and colleague from ''Gone With The Wind'', put Lemmon either inside or in direct proximity to Reeves' bedroom.<ref>Speeding Bullet, 2nd Ed, by Jan Alan Henderson, p. 151</ref>  According to Crane (who was not present), Bill Bliss had told Millicent Trent after the shot rang out, while Bliss was having a drink, that Leonore Lemmon came downstairs and said, \u201cTell them I was down here, tell them I was down here!\u201d<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glasshousepresents.com/Fred_Crane.htm|title=Glass House Presents|publisher=Glass House Presents|accessdate=2010-08-13}}</ref>\n\nA number of questionable physical findings were reported by investigators and others:  No fingerprints were recovered from the gun.  No gunpowder residue was found on Reeves' hands. (Some sources contend that it may not have been looked for, as gunshot residue testing was not routinely performed in 1959.<ref>[http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/1556/was-em-superman-em-star-george-reeves-a-suicide-or-murder-victim \"Was Superman star George Reeves a suicide \u2013 or murder victim?\"], StraightDope.com; accessed October 31, 2015.</ref>)  The bullet that killed Reeves was recovered from the bedroom ceiling, and the spent shell casing was found under his body. Two additional bullets were discovered embedded in the bedroom floor.  All three bullets had been fired from the weapon found at Reeves' feet, though all witnesses agreed they heard only one gunshot, and there was no sign of forced entry or other physical evidence that a second person was in the room.<ref name = \"who\"/>  Despite the unanswered questions, Reeves' death was officially ruled a suicide, based on witness statements, physical evidence at the scene, and the autopsy report.<ref>Los Angeles Police Department Death Report, June 26, 1959.</ref>\n\nReeves' mother thought the ruling premature and peremptory, and retained attorney [[Jerry Giesler]] to petition for a reinvestigation of the case as a possible homicide. The findings of a second autopsy, conducted at Giesler's request, were the same as the first, except for a series of bruises of unknown origin about the head and body. A month later, having uncovered no evidence contradicting the official finding, Giesler announced that he was satisfied that the gunshot wound had been self-inflicted, and withdrew.<ref>''Los Angeles Mirror-News'', June 24, 1959</ref><ref name = \"who\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/04/14/who-killed-superman-the-sinister-true-story-behind-the-death-of/ Who Killed Superman?] ''The Telegraph'' (March 13, 2016), retrieved August 17, 2016.</ref>\n\nReeves is interred at Mountain View Cemetery and Mausoleum in [[Altadena, California]]. His scheduled performance for Kennywood Amusement Park was replaced by [[Guy Williams (actor)|Guy Williams]] as Zorro. In 1960, Reeves was awarded a star on Hollywood's Walk of Fame on Hollywood Boulevard for his contributions to the TV industry.<ref>{{Cite comic| writer=Marx, Barry|cowriters=[[Joey Cavalieri|Cavalieri, Joey]] and Hill, Thomas|artist=Petruccio, Steven|editor=Marx, Barry|story=George Reeves America Loves Superman|title=Fifty Who Made DC Great|date=1985|publisher=DC Comics|page=25}}</ref>  In 1985, he was posthumously named one of the honorees by DC Comics in the company's 50th anniversary publication ''[[Fifty Who Made DC Great]]''.\n\n===Controversy===\nActors [[Alan Ladd]] and [[Gig Young]] were reportedly skeptical of the official determination. Reeves' friend [[Rory Calhoun]] told a reporter \"No one in Hollywood believed the suicide story.\" In their book ''Hollywood Kryptonite'', Sam Kashner and Nancy Schoenberger make a case for the involvement of [[Toni Mannix]], the wife of MGM vice president and fixer [[Eddie Mannix]], with whom Reeves had been having an affair. Others suggested that Eddie Mannix\u2014rumored to have mafia ties\u2014ordered Reeves killed.<ref>[http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2000/12/03/ent_299454.shtml#.WOflWxRGWA0 Death of Superman may not have been a suicide]. ''Augusta Chronicle'' (December 3, 2000), retrieved April 7, 2017.</ref>\n\nThe 2006 film ''[[Hollywoodland]]'', starring [[Ben Affleck]] as Reeves and [[Adrien Brody]] as a fictional investigator loosely based on actual detective Milo Speriglio, dramatizes the investigation of Reeves' death. The film suggests three possible scenarios: accidental shooting by Lemmon, murder by an unnamed hitman under orders from Eddie Mannix, and suicide.\n\nToni Mannix suffered from [[Alzheimer's disease]] for years and died in 1983. In 1999, Los Angeles publicist [[Edward Lozzi]] said that Toni Mannix had confessed to a Catholic priest in Lozzi's presence that she was responsible for having Reeves killed. (This was following the resurrection of the Reeves case by TV shows ''[[Unsolved Mysteries]]'' and ''[[Mysteries and Scandals]]''.) Lozzi made the statement on TV tabloid shows, including ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]'', ''[[Inside Edition]]'', and ''[[Court TV]]''. In the wake of ''Hollywoodland''{{'}}s publicity in 2006, Lozzi repeated his story to the tabloid ''The Globe'' and to the ''Los Angeles Times'', where the statement was disputed by Jack Larson. Larson stated that facts which he knew from his close friendship with Toni Mannix precluded Lozzi's story from being true. According to Lozzi, he lived with and then visited the elderly Mannix from 1979 to 1982 and on at least a half-dozen occasions he called a priest when Mrs. Mannix feared death and wanted to confess her sins. Mannix suffered from Alzheimer's disease and senile dementia, but Lozzi says that her confession was made during a period of lucidity in Mannix's home before she was moved from her house to a hospital. Mannix lived in a hospital suite for the last several years of her life, having donated a large portion of her estate to the hospital in exchange for perpetual care. Lozzi also told of Tuesday night prayer sessions that Toni Mannix conducted with him and others at an altar shrine to Reeves that she had built in her home. Lozzi stated \"During these prayer sessions, she prayed loudly and trance-like to Reeves and God, and without confessing yet, asked them for forgiveness.\" Lozzi's statement, however, is not supported by independent evidence.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=90%\n|+Film\n|-\n! width=3%|Year\n! width=18%|Title\n! width=22%|Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" width=20%| Notes\n|-\n| 1939\n| ''[[Espionage Agent]]''\n| Warrington's secretary\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1939\n| ''[[On Dress Parade]]''\n| Southern soldier in trench\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1939\n| ''[[Gone with the Wind (film)|Gone with the Wind]]''\n| Stuart Tarleton&nbsp;\u2013 Scarlett's beau\n| Credited erroneously onscreen as playing Brent Tarleton (see above)\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''{{sortname|The|Fighting 69th}}''\n| Jack O'Keefe\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Father Is a Prince]]''\n| Gary Lee\n|\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Virginia City (film)|Virginia City]]''\n| Major Drewery's telegrapher\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Tear Gas Squad]]''\n| Joe McCabe\n|\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''Pony Express Days''\n| William F. 'Buffalo Bill' Cody\n| 20 min. short\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Calling All Husbands]]''\n| Dan Williams\n|\n|-\n|  1940\n| ''[[Always a Bride]]''\n|  Mike Stevens\n|\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''{{sortname||'Til We Meet Again|sort=Til We Meet Again}}''\n| Jimmy Coburn\n|\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Torrid Zone]]''\n| Sancho, Rosario's Henchman\n|\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Gambling on the High Seas]]''\n| Newspaper Reporter\n| Not for the Daily Planet\n|-\n| 1940\n| ''[[Knute Rockne, All American]]''\n| Distraught Player\n| Alternative title: ''A Modern Hero'', Uncredited\n|- \n| 1940\n| ''[[Argentine Nights]]''\n| Eduardo 'El Tigre' Estaban\n| Sings in this role\n|-\n| 1941\n| ''{{sortname|The|Strawberry Blonde}}''\n| Harold\n|\n|-\n| 1941\n| ''[[Blood and Sand (1941 film)|Blood and Sand]]''\n| Captain Pierre Lauren\n|\n|-\n| 1941\n| ''[[Lydia (film)|Lydia]]''\n| Bob Willard\n| Alternative title: ''Illusions''\n|-\n| 1941\n| ''[[Man at Large]]''\n| Bob Grayson\n|\n|-\n| 1941\n| ''[[Dead Men Tell]]''\n| Bill Lydig\n|\n|-\n| 1942\n| ''[[Border Patrol (1943 film)|Border Patrol]]''\n| Don Enrique Perez\n|\n|-\n|1942\n| ''[[Blue, White and Perfect]]''\n| Juan Arturo O'Hara\n|\n|-\n| 1942\n| ''[[Sex Hygiene]]''\n| Pool player #1\n| U.S. Army documentary|\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''Bar 20''\n| Lin Bradley\n|\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''[[Colt Comrades]]''\n| Lin Whitlock\n|\n|-\n\n| 1943\n| ''[[So Proudly We Hail!]]''\n| Lt. John Summers\n|\n|-\n| 1943\n| ''[[The Kansan (film)|The Kansan]]''\n| Jesse James\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1944\n| ''[[Winged Victory (film)|Winged Victory]]''\n| Lt. Thompson\n| Credited as Sgt. George Reeves\n|-\n| 1945\n| ''Airborne Lifeboat''\n| Pilot\n|\n|-\