d their Panamanian partner, The Harari Group, designed the kit that El Salvador used. The kit was showcased by the team on February 11, 2009 as they started their [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|FIFA World Cup qualifying]] campaign against [[Trinidad & Tobago national football team|Trinidad & Tobago]] in the [[CONCACAF]] (Central-American Football Union) Hexagonal Cup.<ref name=\"Mitre\">{{cite web | title= Mitre (El Salvador)| url= http://www.mitre.com/el-salvador.html | publisher=[[Mitre Sports International|Mitre]] | accessdate=2010-11-11 | date=2009-03-09}}</ref> On October 22, 2010, the [[Salvadoran Football Association|FESFUT]] extended the contract with Mitre by four years.<ref name=\"Mitre 2014\">{{cite web | title= Mitre and El Salvador extend partnership | url= http://www.mitre.com/news/mitre-and-el-salvador-extend-partnership/ | publisher= [[Mitre Sports International|Mitre]] | accessdate= 2010-11-22 | date= 2010-11-02 | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101223165249/http://www.mitre.com/news/mitre-and-el-salvador-extend-partnership/ | archivedate= 2010-12-23 }}</ref> The first home and away kit made by Mitre feature a [[watermark]] of the country's national shield on the center of the shirt and some horizontal stripes along the kit. The current kit featured white remains along the neck, at the bottom of the kit, and over the shoulders. When this kit was introduced in 2009 it also introduced a new [[logo]] that replaced the typical logo of an \"E\"  and an \"S\" surrounded by a circle.<ref name=\"Kit\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soccershopusa.com/Display_Product_Detail.asp?ProductID=3978&Cat1ID=10&Cat2ID=55&Cat3ID= |title=El Salvador Home Kit |publisher=Soccer Shop USA |accessdate=2010-11-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716101116/http://www.soccershopusa.com/Display_Product_Detail.asp?ProductID=3978&Cat1ID=10&Cat2ID=55&Cat3ID= |archive-date=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\nUmbro has become the new kit supplier of the El Salvador national football team. Replacing Mitre, the first Umbro El Salvador football kits were released June 15, 2017 and were debuted in the 2017 Gold Cup.\n\n==Players==\n===Current squad===\nThe following 23 players have been selected to play in the [[2019 CONCACAF Gold Cup]], set to take place between 15 June and 7 July.\n<br/> ''Caps and goals as of 26 March 2019 after the game against [[Peru national football team|Peru]].\n{{nat fs g start|background=#FF0000|color=#FFFFFF}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=1|pos=GK|name=[[Henry Hern\u00e1ndez]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1985|1|4}}|caps=28|goals=0|club=[[Malacateco]]|clubnat= GUA}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=18|pos=GK|name=[[Kevin Carabantes]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1995|3|20}}|caps=1|goals=0|club=[[C.D. Municipal Lime\u00f1o|Municipal Lime\u00f1o]]|clubnat=SLV}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=22|pos=GK|name=[[\u00d3scar Pleitez]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1993|2|6}}|caps=0|goals=0|club=[[A.D. Isidro Metap\u00e1n|Isidro Metap\u00e1n]]|clubnat=SLV}}\n{{nat fs break|background=#0000DD}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=2|pos=DF|name=[[Juan Barahona]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|6|26}}|caps=67|goals=1|club=[[Sacramento Republic|Sacramento]]|clubnat=USA}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=3|pos=DF|name=[[Roberto Dom\u00ednguez (footballer)|Roberto Dom\u00ednguez]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1997|5|9}}|caps=22|goals=0|club=[[Club Bol\u00edvar|Bol\u00edvar]]|clubnat=BOL}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=4|pos=DF|name=[[Iv\u00e1n Manc\u00eda]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1989|5|1}}|caps=8|goals=0|club=[[Alianza F.C.|Alianza]]|clubnat=SLV}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=5|pos=DF|name=[[Alexander Mendoza]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|6|4}}|caps=37|goals=0|club=[[Santa Tecla F.C.|Santa Tecla]]|clubnat=SLV}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=14|pos=DF|name=[[Rub\u00e9n Marroqu\u00edn]]|age={{birth date and age|df=yes|1992|5|10}}|caps=2|goals=0|club=[[Alianza F.C.|Alianza]]|clubnat=SLV}}\n{{nat fs g player|no=15|pos=DF|na