V}} [[Ra\u00fal Maga\u00f1a]]\n| 1987\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|YUG}} [[Milovan \u0110ori\u0107]]\n| 1988\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|YUG}} [[Miroslav Vuka\u0161inovi\u0107]]\n| 1988\u20131989\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Conrado Miranda]]\n| 1989\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|YUG}} [[Kiril Doj\u010dinovski]]\n| 1989\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[\u00d3scar Emigdio Ben\u00edtez|\u00d3scar Ben\u00edtez]]\n| 1991\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|URU}} [[Jorge Aude]]\n| 1991\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|URU}} [[An\u00edbal Ruiz]]\n| 1992\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|BRA}} [[Jorge Vieira (Brazilian footballer)|Jorge Vieira]]\n| 1993\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|CHI}} [[N\u00e9stor Matamala]]\n| 1993\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Ricardo L\u00f3pez Tenorio|Ricardo Tenorio]]\n| 1993\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|MKD}} [[Kiril Doj\u010dinovski]]\n| 1994\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|ARG}} [[Jos\u00e9 Omar Pastoriza|Jos\u00e9 Pastoriza]]\n| 1995\u20131996\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Armando Contreras Palma|Armando Palma]]\n| 1996\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SER}} [[Milovan \u0110ori\u0107]]\n| 1997\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|MKD}} [[Kiril Doj\u010dinovski]]\n| 1998\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|CHI}} [[Julio Escobar]]\n| 1998\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|BRA}} [[Marinho Peres]]\n| 1999\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Ricardo L\u00f3pez Tenorio|Ricardo Tenorio]]\n| 1999\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[\u00d3scar Emigdio Ben\u00edtez|\u00d3scar Ben\u00edtez]]\n| 1999-2000\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Carlos Recinos]]\n| 2000\u20132002\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Juan Ram\u00f3n Paredes]]\n| 2002\u20132004\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Armando Contreras Palma|Armando Palma]]\n| 2004\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|ARG}} [[Carlos Cavagnaro]]\n| 2005\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Miguel Aguilar Obando|Miguel Aguilar]]\n| 2005\u20132006\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|MEX}} [[Carlos de los Cobos]]\n| 2006\u20132009\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rugamas]]\n| 2010\u20132011\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|URU}} [[Rub\u00e9n Israel]]\n| 2011\u20132012\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|MEX}} [[Juan de Dios Castillo]]\n| 2012\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|Peru}} [[Agust\u00edn Castillo]]\n| 2012\u20132013\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|SLV}} [[Mauricio Alfaro]]\n| 2014\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|Spain}} [[Albert Roca]]\n| 2014\u20132015\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|El Salvador}} [[Jorge Humberto Rodr\u00edguez|Jorge Rodr\u00edguez]]\n| 2015\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|Honduras}} [[Ram\u00f3n Maradiaga]]\n| 2015\u20132016\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|Colombia}} [[Eduardo Lara]]\n| 2016\u20132017\n|-\n| {{Flagicon|MEX}} [[Carlos de los Cobos]]\n| 2018-\n|}\n\nSource:<ref name=\"Directores\"/>\n\n==Records and honors==\n\nEl Salvador were the first Central American team to qualify for a [[FIFA World Cup]], in 1970, and the first Central American team to qualify twice which they achieved with entry into the 1982 World Cup. They were the first Central American team to ever score a goal in a [[1982 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] on June 15, 1982. They were the first Central American country to qualify their football team to the Olympic Games ([[Football at the 1968 Summer Olympics|Mexico 1968]]). They were the first Central American team to sign up for a World Cup qualifier (France 1938). They were the first Central American team to be champions of the [[Football at the Central American and Caribbean Games|Central American and Caribbean Games]] (Mexico 1954). They were also the first Central American team to organize the [[Football at the Central American and Caribbean Games|Central American and Caribbean Games]] (1935) and the first ever [[CONCACAF Championship]] (1963). El Salvador were also the first Central American team to beat [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in Mexico City; by a score of 3\u20132 at the 1954 Central American and Caribbean Games. Scorers of that game are as follows: Mario Montoya 16' (0\u20131), Antonio Jasso 27' (1\u20131), Mario Montoya 36' (1\u20132), [[Ricardo Valencia]] 37' (1\u20133), Rafael Gutierrez 64' (2\u20133).<ref name=\"CAG 1954\"/> The 1st goal in a World Cup qualifier was scored by Joel Estada on 12 December 1968 against [[Suriname national football team|Dutch Guiana]]. The 50th goal in a World Cup qualifier was scored by [[Ever Hern\u00e1ndez]] in a 1\u20130 victory\u2014on 2 December 1981\u2014against Mexico. The 100th goal in a World Cup qualifier was scored by Jorge \"M\u00e1gico\" Gonz\u00e1lez on 2 May 1993 against [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]]. The 150th goal in a World Cup qualifier was scored by [[V\u00edctor Vel\u00e1squez]] in a 2\u20131 victory\u2014on 13 June 2004\u2014against [[Bermuda national football team|Bermuda]]. The 200th goal in a World Cup qualifier was scored by defender [[Xavier Garc\u00eda (footballer)|Xavier Garc\u00eda]] in a 4\u20131 victory\u2014on 6 September 2011\u2014against the [[Cayman Islands national football team|Cayman Islands]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Pablo|title=El gol 200 de El Salvador en eliminatorias|url=http://www.culebritamacheteada.com.sv/2011/09/07/el-gol-200-de-el-salvador-en-eliminatorias/|publisher=culebritamacheteada.com.sv|accessdate=10 September 2011|language=Spanish|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326193842/http://www.culebritamacheteada.com.sv/2011/09/07/el-gol-200-de-el-salvador-en-eliminatorias/|archive-date=26 March 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;Honours\n* '''[[CONCACAF Gold Cup|CONCACAF Championship / CONCACAF Gold Cup]]'''\n** Runner-up (2): [[1963 CONCACAF Championship|1963]],<ref name=\"CONCACAF Nations Cup 1963\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca63.html | title= CONCACAF Nations Cup 1963 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=2004-02-14}}</ref> [[1981 CONCACAF Championship|1981]]<ref name=\"CONCACAF Nations Cup 1981\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca81.html | title= CONCACAF Nations Cup 1981 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=1998-07-13}}</ref>\n** Third place (1): [[1977 CONCACAF Championship|1977]]<ref name=\"CONCACAF Nations Cup 1977\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/conca77.html | title= CONCACAF Nations Cup 1977 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=1998-07-13}}</ref>\n* '''[[UNCAF Nations Cup]]'''\n** Third place (5): [[UNCAF Nations Cup|1995]],<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 1995\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam95.html |title=UNCAF Nations Cup 1995 |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] |accessdate=2010-11-14 |date=2001-11-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514025907/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam95.html |archivedate=2011-05-14 }}</ref> [[UNCAF Nations Cup 1997|1997]],<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 1997\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam97.html | title= UNCAF Nations Cup 1997 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=2003-01-26}}</ref> [[UNCAF Nations Cup 2001|2001]],<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam01.html | title= UNCAF Nations Cup 2001 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=2007-02-21}}</ref> [[UNCAF Nations Cup 2003|2003]]<ref name=\"UNCAF Nations Cup 2003\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/gold-cam03.html | title= UNCAF Nations Cup 2003 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=2005-03-02}}</ref> [[2013 Copa Centroamericana|2013]]\n* '''[[Central American and Caribbean Games]]'''\n** '''Gold Medal (2):''' [[1954 Central American and Caribbean Games|1954]],<ref name=\"CAG 1954\"/> [[Football at the 2002 Central American and Caribbean Games|2002]]<ref name=\"CAG 2002\"/>\n** Third place (1): [[1935 Central American and Caribbean Games|1935]]<ref name=\"CAG 1935\" />\n* '''[[CCCF Championship]]'''\n** '''Winner (1):''' [[1943 CCCF Championship|1943]]<ref name=\"CCCF 1943\"/>\n** Runner-up (2): [[1941 CCCF Championship|1941]],<ref name=\"CCCF 1941\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cccf41.html | title= CCCF Championship 1941 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=2006-05-25}}</ref> [[1961 CCCF Championship|1961]]<ref name=\"CCCF 1961\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/cccf61.html | title= CCCF Championship 1961 | publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]] | accessdate=2010-11-14 | date=1999-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Association football|El Salvador}}\n* [[El Salvador national under-23 football team]]\n* [[El Salvador national under-21 football team]]\n* [[El Salvador national under-17 football team]]\n* [[List of football clubs in El Salvador]]\n* [[Salvadoran Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n de F\u00fatbol Profesional]]\n* [[El Salvador national football team all-time record]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"|\nrefs=\n<ref name=\"Minute goal scored\" group=\"note\">Some notes in this article indicate the time at which a goal was scored; for example, (30') indicates that a goal was scored at the 30th minute. This may also be combined by other goals scored by one player; for example, (30',63') indicates that 2 goals were scored at the 30th minute and 63rd minute by one player\u2014which should be noted right before.</ref>\n<ref name=\"Aggregate score\" group=\"note\">Some notes in this article indicate the two scores that add to the aggregate score; for example, (2\u20130,1\u20131) results in an aggregate score of 3\u20131\u20142\u20130 being the first match played and 1\u20131 being the second match played.</ref>\n<ref name=\"Withdrew\" group=\"note\">El Salvador turned down an invitation from [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]].</ref>\n<ref name=\"1943 Champions\" group=\"note\">El Salvador was crowned champions by goal difference after Guatemala withdrew from the final between the both countries.</ref>\n\n<!-- The following references appeared in the reflist but were not used in the prior text. Please return them to the reflist once they have been correctly cited in the main article.\n<ref name=\"First game\" group=\"note\">The final score of the first match has also been considered to be 3\u20130. Different texts of sports magazines and books on Guatemalan, Salvadoran and Costa Rican football history do not agree with the result obtained.</ref>\n-->\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|El Salvador national association football team}}\n{{external media\n| align = right\n| width = \n| image1 = [http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/CM14-ES3DR2-ElSalvador1.jpg Picture of the Team] }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110810074306/http://www.fesfut.org.sv/ Federaci\u00f3n Salvadore\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol Official Site] {{in lang|es}}\n* [http://www.elbaloncuscatleco.com/ El Salvador national football team (Non-Official Site)] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=slv/ El Salvador - FIFA profile]\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/elsal-intres-detwcq.html El Salvador&nbsp;\u2013 Details of World Cup Qualifiers]\n* [http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/elsal-intres.html 1921 to 2008 El Salvador match results] by ''Barrie Courtney'' at [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[1941 CCCF Championship|1941]] {{Fb-rt|CRC}}\n| title = [[CCCF Championship|CCCF Champions]]\n| years = [[1943 CCCF Championship|1943]] (First title)\n| after = [[CCCF Championship|1946]] {{Fb-rt|CRC}}\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[1950 Central American and Caribbean Games|1950]] [[Cura\u00e7ao national football team|Cura\u00e7ao]] {{Flagicon|Cura\u00e7ao}}\n| title = [[Central American and Caribbean Games|Central American and Caribbean Games Champions]]\n| years = [[1954 Central American and Caribbean Games|1954]] (Second title)\n| after = [[1959 Central American and Caribbean Games|1959]] {{Fb-rt|Mexico}}\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before = [[1998 Central American and Cari